article.description: Jessica Foley scored 14 of her 16 points in the first half to lead second-ranked Duke to an 89-63 victory Wednesday over Rhode Island in the first round of the Auburn Holiday Classic.
article.headline: Blue Devils win with 57 percent shooting
article.linkText: Duke beats Rhode Island for 10th straight win
article.story:
AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- For coach Gail Goestenkors, second-ranked Duke's 89-63 victory over Rhode Island on Wednesday just wasn't good enough and is a source of concern for the next round of the Auburn Holiday Classic.

Duke, while winning its 10th straight game with 57 percent shooting, fell below its 26.8-point victory margin in its first ever matchup against the Rams (2-8).

"I am very disappointed with our effort. We played very poor defense in this game," Goestenkors said. "I am not sure if it's because of the Christmas break, but that is something that we are going to have to improve on if we intend to beat Auburn."

Host Auburn faces Rhode Island on Thursday before taking on Duke in the final round Friday.

Jessica Foley scored 14 of her 16 points in the first half to lead Duke. Foley made 6-of-10 shots -- including three 3-pointers -- for Duke, which led 47-25 at halftime. Mistie Williams and Monique Currie added 14 points apiece for the Blue Devils (12-1).

"We had to get the kinks out today after having a stretch of eight days without a game. We were a little off with our passes, were not making layups and didn't play well defensively," Foley said.

Williams also blamed the lengthy break for Duke's weaker defense.

"Coming off a break like we had, we have to get our communication back on defense as that is what makes our defense what it is," she said. "It was disappointing how we came out and played on the defensive end today. It showed our lack of focus."

Duke's 22 turnovers was a blow to the Blue Devils, who notched a season-low seven turnovers in their 81-31 victory over Ball State on Dec. 23.

Tanya Rhodes scored 17 points on 8-of-18 shooting to lead Rhode Island. Peta Kneen added 13 points for the Rams.

Coach Tom Garrick said his players' image of Duke intimidated them, especially in the first half.

"I think our team bought into the myth of Duke a little too much," he said. "That is not to say they are not great because they are. But when we came out we played the first 20 minutes kind of shell-shocked."

Duke opened the game with a 16-4 surge and led by as many as 27 points in the second half. Currie and Chante Black had six rebounds each for Duke, which dominated the boards 43-25.

Rhode Island made 50 percent of its shots in the second half but was held to 44 percent shooting overall.

"I think the second 20 minutes we really picked it up and played well," Garrick said. "I just wish that we would have been able to do that in the first half instead of waiting until the second half."
